            <p class="padding-top">An important thing to remember about '<em>beon</em>' and '<em>wesan</em>'
                is that they are used to mean slightly different forms of being. For example, the verb
                '<em>wesan</em>' is generally used to express the present form of 'to be'. For example, '<em>Se stan is micel - the stone is big</em>'. While '<em>beon</em>'
                tends to be used to express permanent truths or the future tense. For example, '<em>I am your God</em>'.
            </p>
